MEMORANDUM FOR: Deputy Director for Administration
FROM:
SA/DDA
SUBJECT: MKULTRA Notification Program - Progress Report
1. This memorandum is intended to let you know what I am doing and what I propose to do.
2. a. Summaries of the 149 MKULTRA projects prepared by
OTS and the IG and the .
categorization of those projects prepared by the Office of the
General Counsel have been reviewed.
b. Files on all projects where there is any suggestion
of human testing have been reviewed in detail and a separate summary sheet prepared for each suggesting what action needs to be
taken.
c. Seven Memorandums for the Record have been prepared and sent to OGC and OMS for concurrence covering_l2 of the
more straightforward projects. If OGC and OMS concur, these projects are closed out.
d. Draft letters have been prepared to the University
of Oklahoma, the Michigan Department of Mental Health, and Dr. -
Harold A. Abramson. These drafts have been sent to OGC for review
and contribution of some language to cover the legal niceties of
the Privacy Act and whatever other statutes may apply. Probably
we will hold external correspondence until it is all completed so
everything will hit the fan at once.
e. Components of the Agency have been asked to report
on the status of their record reviews and give an expression of
their confidence that there are no more drug related programs.

## MKULTRA NOTIFICATION PROG[12888107].pdf - Page 2

Responses have been received from all but NFAC and DDSGT. Responses
received are favorable; the office of Security and DDO have a few more
records to look at and have promised follow-up reports in a few weeks.
f. A composite list of drugs used in MKULTRA projects
has been compiled and OSI has been requested to check them against
their computer file to produce a printout that will describe pharmacological characteristics of those found. When we receive this
report in the next several days we will know what help we may require from outside sources, HEW presumably, for evaluation of long
term effects.
g. Names of individual researchers identified in the
MKULTRA files have been listed by project. DDO has been requested
to make available for review any 201 files they may find on these
people and the Office of Security has been asked to run name checks
and give us file summaries. These searches are not complete but
the responses so far are informative and encouraging - none of
them suggest any different areas of concern.
h. Names of principal private researchers have been
searched through Who's Who in America and similar library sources.
Those most deeply involved represent an impressive array of resources.
i. One current employee who was a volunteer, witting
subject of an experiment conducted in the New York safehouse by
Agency staff employees has been interviewed.
j. UTS, is working with me virtually
full time. .
k. 23 MKULTRA projects await action. 'They fall into
seven groups according to institution or investigator. I am proceeding with the review of those groups and preparation of appro- »
priate correspondence. .
1. We will soon start writing or calling former employees
to request interviews to test their recollections.
3." Until we had our session with the General Counsel last
Thursday, I felt reasonably satisfied with our methodology and the progress we are making. We are not waiting idly for him' to redefine and
expand the problem beyond drug experimentation. Regardless of how that
comes out, we still will have to do what we are doing with MKULTRA. I
am sure you find this fascinating and wait with baited breath for
chapter 2 .

## MKULTRA PROGRAM[12884313].pdf - Page 1

29 November 1963 -'
MEMORANDUM FOR THE RECORD
SUBJECT : NKULTRA PROGRAM
1. A meeting was held in General Carter's office on 29 Nove_—_—,b=-r_
1963 to discuss the subject program. Those present, in addition to
General Carter, were Messrs. Helms, Kirkpatrick, '\Gottlieb,
and Barman. The main thrust of the discussion was the testing of
certain drugs on unwitting U. S. citizens. Dr. Gottlieb gave a brief
history of the MKULTRA program which was not in any way at variance
with the IG report of August 1963 on this subject. "
2. Messrs. Gottlieb andj _;!argued for the continuation of
unwitting testing, using as the principal point that controlled testing
cannot be depended upon for accurate results. General Carter, Ivir.
Kirkpatrick, and I do not disagree with this point. We also accept the
necessity for having a "stable of drugs" on the shelf and the requirement
for continued research and development of drugs--not omy for possible
operational use but also to give CIA insight on the state of the art in this
field and in particular to alert us to what the opposition is or might be
expected to do in the R&D and employment of drugs. '
_'_noted that there was no disagreernentwith the
recommendations of the IG survey on MKULTRA with the exception of
the unwitting testing problem. In response to a query from General
Carter, he stated that since the IG report such testing has been held in ~
abeyance. -
4. General Carter made it clear that he understood the necessity
for research and development of all types of drugs, to include their testing
However, he was troubled by the "unwitting aspect". This led to a brief'
discussion on the possibility of unwitting tests on foreign nationals, but
according to' - 'ithis had been ruled out as a result of several
conversations he recently had with senior chiefs of stations—-too dangerous
and the lack of controlled facilities. (This seemed an odd conclusion

## MKULTRA PROGRAM[12884313].pdf - Page 2

to me since the same dangers exist in the U. S. and from what we
were able to ﬁnd out during our survey, the facilities we have for
uncontrolled testing leave much to be desired--I made a point of this.)
5. After further discussion, it was agreed: '
a.. That the charter of MIKULTRA would be revised
along the lines recommended in the IG survey._
b. The procedures £<>r testing drugs are to be reviewed
and new alternative proposals submitted. '
c. If .it_ is concluded by the DD] P that unwitting testing - '
on American citizens must be continued to operationally prove out these drugs, it may become
necessary to place this problem before the Director_
for a decision. _" -
5. I made the point that the IG survey had found other problems
with the MKULTRA program in addition to the unwitting testing, but
stated if the charter is rewritten along the lines recommended,I
believe these problems would be corrected. _ _ _
7.. NOTE: The IG Survey of MKULTRA was handed to
\after the meeting for his usein redrattiaig the charter. '
J. S aréman '
Inspec r General
